        <page n="01" image="pa.fr.fr.1863.09.09.01">
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>The National Cemetery</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Prints a letter from D. M. McConaughy to McClure and Stoner suggesting the
                    establishment of a National cemetery at Gettysburg. The editors argue that the
                    difficulties of body identification makes difficult the separation of soldiers
                    by states.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>Why A Democrat Supports Curtin</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary>"The Huntingdon Globe, a journal that was the accepted Democratic organ
                    in Huntingdon County for many years, and earnestly opposed Curtin's election in
                    1860, announces its purpose to subordinate the Democratic party to the interests
                    of the country, and has hoisted the Curtin flag. It thus sensibly and
                    patriotically reasons on the subject;"</commentary>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Recounts the Huntingdon Globe's support of Curtin.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Andrew G. Curtin</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Provides a detailed account of Andrew G. Curtin's youth, education, and
                    political career including his support of Henry Clay.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>6</column>
                <head>The Rights Of Slavery</head>
                <origin>The Eaton Reporter</origin>
                <commentary>"Hon. Lewis D. Campbell, of Ohio, has written the following pointed and
                    sensible letter to the Eaton Reporter on the rights of rebels who have arrayed
                    themselves against the government."</commentary>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Reprints Lewis D. Campbell's statement that those who revolted against a
                    government and constitution that gave the right of slavery deserved to lose that
                    right.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>6</column>
                <head>Hon. Thaddeus Stevens</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Clarifies the procedure of obtaining exemption by supplying a substitute or
                    paying $300.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote/>
        </page>
