            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>Agricultural. Seed And Seeding</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Discusses the preparation of the ground for different types of plants.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="l">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Washington. The Deserted Capitol--President Lincoln--Generals Halleck and
                    Heintzelman--Secretaries Stanton and Chase--Gov. Curtin--Removal of the Sick and
                    Wounded Soldiers to Pennsylvania</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer>"A. K. M."</trailer>
                <names/>
                <summary>Provides general descriptions of the few notables left in an otherwise
                    deserted Washington.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="l">
                <column>3</column>
                <head>Ford's New Theatre--Arrivals in Washington--Moseby's Raids--The Baltimore and
                    Ohio Railroad</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer>Norval</trailer>
                <names/>
                <summary>Describes the opening of Ford Theatre; the arrival of notable
                    Pennsylvanians in Washington including Curtin, Covode, and McClure; John
                    Moseby's raids, and the resumption of service on the Baltimore and Ohio
                    Railroad.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="l">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>New York. A Trip to Port Jervis--History of the Deer-Park--The
                    Tri-States-Huguenot Village--Its History--Summer Resort</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer>"Enigma"</trailer>
                <names/>
                <summary>Describes the sights in and around the Port Jervis area.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>5</column>
                <head>Resisting Laws</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Reminds readers that Gen. Jackson, in his Farewell Address, said that until
                    a law is proven unconstitutional or is repealed by Congress, the citizens are
                    obligated to follow that law.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote>The page includes advertisements.</pageNote>
